07322nam a22010215i 9780812298307DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122983077 a10.9783/97808122983072doi  a(DE-B1597)577451  a(OCoLC)1265462168  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aK3258 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a342.122304aThe Changing Terrain of Religious Freedom /ced. by Jeffrey Edward Green, Heather J. Sharkey. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemocracy, Citizenship, and Constitutionalism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Landscape of Religious Freedom -- tPart I. Ethical Arguments -- t1. A Right of Its Own: A Case for the Human Right of Religious Freedom -- t2. Can Freedom of Religion or Belief (FoRB) Be Universal? -- tPart II. The Social Contingency of Religious Freedom Disputes -- t3. Microclimates of Religious Freedom: Global Norms Meet Local Conditions in Territorial Hawai`i and Occupied Japan -- t4. The Protection of Religion as “Culture” and “History”: Three Case Studies -- t5. “Baptism of Ire”: Atheist Plaintiffs and Irreligious Freedom in Postwar America -- t6. The Heads or Tails of Cow Protection in India: Religious Freedom and Secular Agriculture -- t7. Bad Faith: Religious Fraud and Religious Freedom in the “Mighty I AM” Case -- tPart III. The (Mis)application of Religious Freedom -- t8. The Historian’s Pickaxe: Uncovering the Racist Origins of the Religious Right -- t9. Female Genital Cutting in Michigan: How Advocates of the Dawoodi Bohra Distorted Religious Freedom to Control Women’s Sexual Conduct -- t10. The U.S. Supreme Court and the Future of Religious Freedom in the United States -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Changing Terrain of Religious Freedom offers theoretical, historical, and legal perspectives on religious freedom, while examining its meaning as an experience, value, and right. The volume starts from the premise that the terrain of religious freedom has never been easy and smooth. Across societies and throughout history, defending or contesting principles of religious freedom has required compromise among multiple interests, balancing values, and wrangling with the law.Drawing on examples from the United States and around the world, and approaching the subject from the disciplines of history, law, sociology, philosophy, religious studies, and political science, the essays in this volume illustrate these challenges. They sketch the contours of contemporary debates while showing how the landscape of religious freedom has shifted over time. They consider various stakeholders that have asserted competing claims, among them individuals and groups; members of minority and majority communities; states and corporations (including both religious organizations and businesses); and believers and non-believers. Taken together, the studies in this volume suggest that understanding religious freedom means grappling with conflicting and perhaps irreconcilable claims about whose rights should prevail over others, what religion is or may be, and how religion should relate to other cultural values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aAtheism.  aChurch and State.  aConstitutional law.  aFreedom of conscience.  aHuman rights.  aRacism and Religious Right.  aReligion and politics.  aReligion.  aReligious Freedom and the Supreme Court.  aReligious freedom.  aReligious liberty.  aUnbelief.  aUniversal rights.1 aAdcock, Cassie, econtributo